As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

In  that  spirit  we  are  looking  to  implement  one  of  the  two  possible  plans  that  these objectives  are  neing  met.  One  plan  is  to  form  a  company  review  committee  consisting  of  production  managers,  production  line  workers,  inspectors  and  a  consultatnt  in quality  controll. As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

In het traditionele China werd van de literatuur geist dat ze waar was, dat ze een juiste weergaven van de morele situatie en de daardoor opgeroepen gevoelens was.  De literatuur kon haar algemeenvormende functie slechts vervullen wanneer zij de waarheid leerde, en dat kon zij slechts doen wanneer zij een juiste weergave was van de in zijn verscheidenheid in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg.  De meest algemene term voor het begrip literatuur in het Chinees is 'wen'.  Dit woord heeft een brede scala van betekenissen die alle afgeleid zijn van de grondbetekenis van een regelmatig terugkerend patroon, zoals dat bijvoorbeeld ontstaat in een weefsel: 'wen' is de zichtbaren vorm van een immanente structuur.  Het woord voor de in elk aspect van de werkelijkheid als onderdeel van de Weg aanwezige rede, principe, structuur, is 'li'.  Het afzonderlijke schriftteken dat ook 'wen' kan worden genoemd, geeft dus de essentile trekken van het aangeduide object weer (vanzelfsprekend wordt hierbij uitgegaan van de pictogrammen en ideogrammen), is het object zelf, zodat Chinese lexicografen vaak de betekenis van
In het traditionele China werd van de literatuur geist dat ze waar was, dat ze een juiste weergave van de morele situatie en de daardoor opgeroepen gevoelens was.  De literatuur kon haar algemeen-vormende functie slechts vervullen wanneer zij de waarheid leerde, en dat kon zij slechts doen wanneer zij een juiste weergave was van de in zijn verscheidenheid in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg.  De meest algemene term voor het begrip literatuur in het Chinees is 'wen'.  Dit woord heeft een brede scala van betekenissen die alle afgeleid zijn van de grondbetekenis van een regelmatig terugkerend patroon, zoals dat bijvoorbeeld ontstaat in een weefsel: 'wen' is de zichtbare vorm van een immanente structuur.  Het woord voor de in elk aspect van de werkelijkheid als onderdeel van de Weg aanwezige rede, principe, structuur, is 'li'.  Het afzonderlijke schriftteken dat ook 'wen' kan worden genoemd, geeft dus de essentile trekken van het aangeduide object weer (vanzelfsprekend wordt hierbij uitgegaan van de pictogrammen en ideogrammen), is het object zelf, zodat Chinese lexicografen vaak de betekenis van een woord zullen afleiden uit de vorm van het karakter.  Door een gebeurtenis, een situatie en het daardoor opgeroepen gevoel te formuleren, legt de tekst evenzo de in elk aspect van de historische werkelijkheid aanwezige 'li' bloot, de tekst maakt de wereld begrijpelijk.  Als belichaming van de 'li' vertoont de tekst ook zelf een duidelijke ordening.  Literatuur is de geordende verwoording van de in de ogenschijnlijk chaotische werkelijkheid immanente Weg.  Ze is als zodanig onvermijdelijk didactisch.  Desondanks is er sprake van een voortdurende spanning tussen die critici die onder de slogan "teksten dienen als voertuig van de Weg" willen dat de literatuur uitdrukkelijk moralistisch is, en die critici die de uitspraak "pozie is het verwoorden van gevoelens" naar voren schuiven en vertrouwen op het onvermijdelijke didactische karakter van de formulering van alle oprechte normale gevoelens.  Om een betrouwbare weergave van de in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg te zijn, moeten de in de literatuur beschreven gebeurtenissen waar gebeurd zijn.  Waarheid is het wezen van de literatuur.  Geen betere teksten dat de Klassieken, die de feilloze formulering van de Weg door de heilige vorsten en wijze ambtsdragers uit de oudheid vormen, welke door een voortdurende zelfvervolmaking een volledig inzicht bezaten in de Weg.  De gehele verdere literatuur wordt beschouwd als een voortzetting van de Klassieken, zowel naar vorm als naar inhoud.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of the two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

AS a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our custome satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired result through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee conveying early in September to draft ideas for imporvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not that changes are effective.  At that time, we migh want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. the patient is a,male widowed buisnessman,born January 12,1928 who has been diagnosed with Prostatic carcenoma and is being regularly treated with flexable sigmoidoscopy on account of perinatal discomfort. The patient is a male, widowed businessman, born January 12, 1928, who has been diagnosed with prostatic carcinoma and is being regularly treated with flexible sigmoidoscopy on account of perianal discomfort.  The patient was observed for several years to present an incrementally rising level of prostatic antigen and negative interval biopsy specimens.  A course of radiation therapy was completed this year after a positive biopsy report for local prostate cancer.  Subsequently there has been no evidence of metastatic disease or of constitutional or skeletal symptoms, and the patient appears to exhibit excellent mental health.  However, he has complained of chronic lower back discomfort and stiffness sufficient to warrant an MRI which showed no major abnormalities.  He has had recurring back spasms and stiffness but no radicular pain or past radiculopathy.  There has been no change in these symptoms, but his current mental health is good and he has a positive psychological attitude towards his cancer diagnosis.  No nocturia or other major voiding symptoms are reported.  Recent PSA equals 2.6.  A regular examination is recommended before the end of the year.  Other medical history includes remote tonsillectomy and adenoidectomy and excision of basal cell carcinoma from mouth in 1984.  There has been no past history of urinary tract infection.  No current medications are used.  There are no known drug allergies.  Review of endocrine systems reveals no known diabetes or thyroid disease.  Patient had positive PPD in 1965 after military service, but chest x-rays were normal with no INH preventive therapy.  No history of asthma or other respiratory symptoms.  No cardiovascular, GI or GU tract symptoms are present.  No history of anemia or other hematopoietic symptoms.  No headaches or other neurologic symptoms.  Musculoskeletal symptoms include apparent bicipital tendinitis on the right shoulder several months ago but now improved.  In general, the patient appears to be a healthy male.  Vital signs are normal as indicated in the attached report.  Skin shows no rashes or suspicious lesions.  No apparent lymphatic symptoms.  Neck and thyroid not palpable.  Lungs are clear.  Heart rate and rhythm are regular.  Abdomen is flat and not tender.  Extremities appear normal except for slight left bicipital groove tenderness.  In addition, downward movement on abducted arms provokes anterior discomfort.  A neurologic examination was not performed.  External genitalia appear normal.  Rectal exam presents slight diffuse prostate enlargement with no areas of hardness or nodularity.  Stools were negative for occult blood.  Informed consent was obtained and discussed for flexible sigmoidoscopy which revealed no mucosal abnormalities or lesions.  Minimal edema of distal rectum was seen but no erythema, friability or other markers of inflammation.  Impression is of an essentially normal rectosigmoid with no clear radiation proctitis.  The patient's habits and history reveal that he is a nonsmoker, social drinker and takes no illicit drugs.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfactio. In that spirit, we are looking to mplment one or two possible plans to ensure that tehse
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One pln is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

as a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-linne workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee couls also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.
In het traditionele China werd van de literatuur geist dat ze waar was, dat ze een juiste weergave van de morele situatie en de daardoor opgeroepen gevoelens was.  De literatuur kon haar algemeen-vormende functie slechts vervullen wanneer zij de waarheid leerde, en dat kon zij slechts doen wannneer zijn een juiste weergave was van de in zijn verscheidenheid in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg.  De meest algemene term voor het begrip literatuur in het Chinees is 'wen'.  Dit woord heeft een brede scala van betekenissen die alle afgeleid zijn van de grondbetekenis van een regelmatig terugkerend patroon, zoals dat bijvoorbeeld ontstaat in een weefsel: 'wen' is de zichtbare vorm van een immanente structuur.  Het woord voor de in elk aspect van de werkelijkheid als onderdeel van de Weg aanwezige rede, principe, structuur, is 'li'.  Het afzonderlijke schriftteken dat ook 'wen' kan worden genoemd, geeft dus de essentile trekken van het aangeduide object weer (vanzelfsprekend wordt hierbij uitgegaan van de pictogrammen en ideogrammen), is het object zelf, zodat Chinese lexicografen vaak de betekenis van een woord zullen afleiden uit de vorm van het karakter.  Door een gebeurtenis, een situatie en het daardoor opgeroepen
In het traditionele China werd van de literatuur geist dat ze waar was, dat ze een juiste weergave van de morele situatie en de daardoor opgeroepen gevoelens was.  De literatuur kon haar algemeen-vormende functie slechts vervullen wanneer zij de waarheid leerde, en dat kon zij slechts doen wanneer zij een juiste weergave was van de in zijn verscheidenheid in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg.  De meest algemene term voor het begrip literatuur in het Chinees is 'wen'.  Dit woord heeft een brede scala van betekenissen die alle afgeleid zijn van de grondbetekenis van een regelmatig terugkerend patroon, zoals dat bijvoorbeeld ontstaat in een weefsel: 'wen' is de zichtbare vorm van een immanente structuur.  Het woord voor de in elk aspect van de werkelijkheid als onderdeel van de Weg aanwezige rede, principe, structuur, is 'li'.  Het afzonderlijke schriftteken dat ook 'wen' kan worden genoemd, geeft dus de essentile trekken van het aangeduide object weer (vanzelfsprekend wordt hierbij uitgegaan van de pictogrammen en ideogrammen), is het object zelf, zodat Chinese lexicografen vaak de betekenis van een woord zullen afleiden uit de vorm van het karakter.  Door een gebeurtenis, een situatie en het daardoor opgeroepen gevoel te formuleren, legt de tekst evenzo de in elk aspect van de historische werkelijkheid aanwezige 'li' bloot, de tekst maakt de wereld begrijpelijk.  Als belichaming van de 'li' vertoont de tekst ook zelf een duidelijke ordening.  Literatuur is de geordende verwoording van de in de ogenschijnlijk chaotische werkelijkheid immanente Weg.  Ze is als zodanig onvermijdelijk didactisch.  Desondanks is er sprake van een voortdurende spanning tussen die critici die onder de slogan "teksten dienen als voertuig van de Weg" willen dat de literatuur uitdrukkelijk moralistisch is, en die critici die de uitspraak "pozie is het verwoorden van gevoelens" naar voren schuiven en vertrouwen op het onvermijdelijke didactische karakter van de formulering van alle oprechte normale gevoelens.  Om een betrouwbare weergave van de in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg te zijn, moeten de in de literatuur beschreven gebeurtenissen waar gebeurd zijn.  Waarheid is het wezen van de literatuur.  Geen betere teksten dat de Klassieken, die de feilloze formulering van de Weg door de heilige vorsten en wijze ambtsdragers uit de oudheid vormen, welke door een voortdurende zelfvervolmaking een volledig inzicht bezaten in de Weg.  De gehele verdere literatuur wordt beschouwd als een voortzetting van de Klassieken, zowel naar vorm als naar inhoud.

In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objrctives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods abd the purchase of additional equipment.  a
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council woul brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to for a company revire committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constasntly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfactio.  In that spiritm we are looking yo implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a compapny review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.
