As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.
In het traditionele CHina werd van de literatuur geist dat ze waas was, dat ze een juiste weergave van de morele situatie en de daardoor opgeroepen gevoelens was.  De literatuur kon haar algemeen-vormende fuctie selchts vervullen wanneer zij de waarheid leerde, en dat kon ze slechts doen wanneer zij een juiste weergave was van de in zijn verscheidenheid in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg.  De meest algemene term voor het begrip literatuur in het Chinees is 'wen'.  Dit woord heenft een brede scale van betekenissen die alle afgeleid zijn van de grondbetekenis van een regelmatig terugkerend patroon, zoals dat bijvoorbeeld ontstaat in een weefsel: 'wen' is de zichtbare vorm van een immanente structuur.  Het woord voor de in elk aspect van de werkelijkheid als onderdeel van de Weg aanwezige rede, principe, structuus is 'lil'.  Het afzonderlijke schriftteken dat ook 'wen' kan worden genoemd, geeft dus de essentile trekken van het aangeduide object weer (vanzelfsprekend wordt hierbij
In het traditionele China werd van de literatuur geist dat ze waar was, dat ze een juiste weergave van de morele situatie en de daardoor opgeroepen gevoelens was.  De literatuur kon haar algemeen-vormende functie slechts vervullen wanneer zij de waarheid leerde, en dat kon zij slechts doen wanneer zij een juiste weergave was van de in zijn verscheidenheid in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg.  De meest algemene term voor het begrip literatuur in het Chinees is 'wen'.  Dit woord heeft een brede scala van betekenissen die alle afgeleid zijn van de grondbetekenis van een regelmatig terugkerend patroon, zoals dat bijvoorbeeld ontstaat in een weefsel: 'wen' is de zichtbare vorm van een immanente structuur.  Het woord voor de in elk aspect van de werkelijkheid als onderdeel van de Weg aanwezige rede, principe, structuur, is 'li'.  Het afzonderlijke schriftteken dat ook 'wen' kan worden genoemd, geeft dus de essentile trekken van het aangeduide object weer (vanzelfsprekend wordt hierbij uitgegaan van de pictogrammen en ideogrammen), is het object zelf, zodat Chinese lexicografen vaak de betekenis van een woord zullen afleiden uit de vorm van het karakter.  Door een gebeurtenis, een situatie en het daardoor opgeroepen gevoel te formuleren, legt de tekst evenzo de in elk aspect van de historische werkelijkheid aanwezige 'li' bloot, de tekst maakt de wereld begrijpelijk.  Als belichaming van de 'li' vertoont de tekst ook zelf een duidelijke ordening.  Literatuur is de geordende verwoording van de in de ogenschijnlijk chaotische werkelijkheid immanente Weg.  Ze is als zodanig onvermijdelijk didactisch.  Desondanks is er sprake van een voortdurende spanning tussen die critici die onder de slogan "teksten dienen als voertuig van de Weg" willen dat de literatuur uitdrukkelijk moralistisch is, en die critici die de uitspraak "pozie is het verwoorden van gevoelens" naar voren schuiven en vertrouwen op het onvermijdelijke didactische karakter van de formulering van alle oprechte normale gevoelens.  Om een betrouwbare weergave van de in al het bestaande aanwezige Weg te zijn, moeten de in de literatuur beschreven gebeurtenissen waar gebeurd zijn.  Waarheid is het wezen van de literatuur.  Geen betere teksten dat de Klassieken, die de feilloze formulering van de Weg door de heilige vorsten en wijze ambtsdragers uit de oudheid vormen, welke door een voortdurende zelfvervolmaking een volledig inzicht bezaten in de Weg.  De gehele verdere literatuur wordt beschouwd als een voortzetting van de Klassieken, zowel naar vorm als naar inhoud.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As acompany, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objective are being met. One plan is to form a company review commitee consisting of production managers, production -line worjers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstore wat to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The commitee could also make suggestion
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as sell as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a conosultant in quality control.  This council would brainstrom ways to increase the quality of production and inpsection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equitment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At the time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet agin October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommeded changes could be implemented in
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirt, we are looking to implentment on of two possiable plans to wnsure that these objectives are being met. One plan
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committtee could meet again in Octobr to report back their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer setisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to impliement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of productio managers, production-line worker, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This counsil would brainstorm ways to increase the quality
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inpsectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back their findings and decide upon new procedures for out manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

In that spirit, we are l;ooking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additonal equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the new committee convening early September to draft ideas for improvements.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve out products, as well as out customer satisfaction. In that sprit, we are looking to implement one of two possible palns to ensue that these objsectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction. In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met. One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control. This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment. A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements. At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans. The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection. Their recommended changes could be implemented in November. Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective. At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company. They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers. If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively. An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own. Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries. Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality. After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products. Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment. In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect. By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant. Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving. Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality. Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions. Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production maagers, production- line workers, inspectors and consultant in quality control. RThis council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of pproduction and inspection methods. The committee could also make suggestions on the steps
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

He's also really old.  the quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.  The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog. As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.

As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satsifaction.  In that spirt, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these onjectives are being met.  On plan is to form a company review commitee consisting of production mamagers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  Thsi council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspections methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on steps necessary tp achieve the desired results through new training methods and teh purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the commitee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams
As a company, we constantly strive to improve our products, as well as our customer satisfaction.  In that spirit, we are looking to implement one of two possible plans to ensure that these objectives are being met.  One plan is to form a company review committee consisting of production managers, production-line workers, inspectors, and a consultant in quality control.  This council would brainstorm ways to increase the quality of production and inspection methods.  The committee could also make suggestions on the steps necessary to achieve the desired results through new training methods and the purchase of additional equipment.  A possible timeline would begin with the committee convening early in September to draft ideas for improvements.  At that time, they could also designate teams to investigate different methods for accomplishing the plans.  The committee could meet again in October to report back on their findings and decide upon new procedures for our manufacturing and inspection.  Their recommended changes could be implemented in November.  Once the changes are made, a future meeting could be scheduled to determine whether or not the changes are effective.  At that time, we might want to establish the committee as part of our company.  They could meet every month or so to ensure that we are maintaining the highest standards in the quality of our products and the satisfaction of our customers.  If necessary, we could maintain the consultant or hire a full-time quality-control person to see that the recommendations of the committee are implemented promptly and effectively.  An alternative plan calls for a select committee of executives to survey methods of quality control used at companies most similar to our own.  Such companies could include Ajax Manufacturing, the Leviathan Corporation and Olympus Industries.  Under this plan, the executive committee could compile a list of methods used by our rivals to achieve high quality.  After all of the data are compiled, the executive committee would determine which methods would best be adopted to maintain top-notch quality in our products.  Once the new techniques are determined, the executives could purchase any necessary equipment.  In addition, they may also decide upon additional training for managers, workers and inspectors in order to put the new methods into effect.  By presenting employees with a completed plan, rather than asking for suggestions and recommendations, we can save needed time and the cost of hiring an outside consultant.  Under this plan, the executive committee could meet with managers and inspectors weekly to see that the new methods are being properly implemented and that the quality of our products is improving.  Once the initial recommendations are implemented, it might be wise to begin rotating the membership of this committee so all executives could become involved in the drive for higher quality.  Rotating the membership would also allow executives to bring their special expertise to the problem and offer some fresh insights and suggestions.  Please consider the two possible plans and bring your thoughts to our staff meeting next week.
